    <name>
      <text>Finding the reciprocal of decimal numbers using a table of reciprocals</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Use a <strong>table of reciprocals</strong> to find the reciprocal of <strong>{@a@}</strong>.</p>
<p>Give your answer to 4 decimal places.</p>
<p>Reciprocal of \({@a@} =\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked Solution</h3>
<p>
To find the reciprocal of \({@a@}\) (which is \(\frac{1}{@a@}\)) using a mathematical table, follow the steps below.
</p>

<p>
1. In the table of reciprocals, move down the column labelled \(x\) until you locate the row <strong>{@float(part_a)@}</strong>.
</p>

<p>
2. From this row, move across to the main column headed <strong>{@part_b@}</strong>.
</p>

<p>
3. Read the number at the intersection of this row and column.<br>
This value is <strong>{@a_1_answer@}</strong>.
</p>

<p>
4. Next, move further along the same row to the <strong>"SUBTRACT"</strong> column (Mean Difference) headed <strong>{@part_c@}</strong>.<br>
The number you find here is the mean difference, which is <strong>{@sub_num@}</strong> (in the last decimal places).
</p>

<p>
5. <strong>Subtract</strong> this mean difference from your first value.<br>
(Note: We subtract because the reciprocal function \(\frac{1}{x}\) decreases as \(x\) increases).
</p>

<p>
\[ {@a_1_answer@} - 0.000{@sub_num@} = {@ta@} \]
</p>

<p>
Therefore, using the table of reciprocals, the reciprocal of \({@a@}\) is <strong>{@ta@}</strong>.
</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
